om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPACMan</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bill Ackman runs a big hedge fund call=
ed=C2=A0Pershing Square Capital Management LP. Since 2012, he has also=C2=
=A0run a public investment company called <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly9wZXJzaGluZ3NxdWFyZWhvbGR=
pbmdzLmNvbS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8c7d7b33" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Pershing Square Holdings Ltd.</a>, wh=
ich=C2=A0provides more capital for Ackman to invest. He has occasionally <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTMtMDctMDgvYWNrbWFuLXJ=
haXNlcy1tb25leS1mb3ItYWN0aXZpc3Qtc3Rha2UtaW4tbGFyZ2UtY29tcGFueQ/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBe370dbe3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> raised single-stock funds</a>, where people give him money t=
o invest in a single company=E2=80=99s stock rather than just investing in =
that stock themselves.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, Ack=
man <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.26002=
3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjMvY=
mlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMtYS1tYXR1cmUtdW5pY29ybg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB635f=
baeb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> did=
 yet another thing</a>. It was a boom year for special purpose acquisition =
companies, a structure in which a financial celebrity raises money from pub=
lic investors in a blind pool to merge with some private company to be name=
d later and take it public. As a big financial celebrity who is good at rai=
sing money, Ackman decided to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjMvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMtYS1tYXR1cmUtdW5pY29ybg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC635fbaeb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> do the biggest SPAC ever</a>. He raised $4 billion f=
or his SPAC, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503=
919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MTE4ODIv=
MDAwMTE5MzEyNTIwMTk3Nzc2L2Q5MzAwNTVkNDI0YjQuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4=
e76d916" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">P=
ershing Square Tontine Holdings</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you=
 run a hedge fund, or a publicly listed hedge-fund-y vehicle, more money is=
 basically good: The more money you have, the more flexibility you have to =
make lots of good investments.[1] But with a SPAC, too much money can be so=
rt of constraining. You=E2=80=99re looking to do one deal, to merge with on=
e private company, typically for a minority stake =E2=80=94=C2=A0call it ar=
ound 10% to 20% =E2=80=94=C2=A0of the company. So a $4 billion SPAC is look=
ing for a $20+ billion merger partner. And that understates things. Ackman,=
 after all, runs a hedge fund (Pershing Square) and also a public hedge-fun=
d-y investment vehicle (Pershing Square Holdings); if he finds a cool inves=
tment for Pershing Square Tontine, it would be awkward to freeze=C2=A0his o=
ther funds out of that investment. So the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZ=
lcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MTE4ODIvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIwMTk3Nzc2L2Q5MzAwNTVkNDI0YjQuaH=
Rt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4e76d916" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;">SPAC offering document</a> said that the other =
Pershing Square funds would invest at least $1 billion, and as much as $3 b=
illion or even more, in any deal that Pershing Square Tontine does.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Ackman was really only looking to do one deal w=
ith a private company worth, say, $40 billion or more. There just aren=E2=
=80=99t that many companies like that, particularly not ones looking to go =
public by merging with a SPAC run by a famous activist investor. He looked =
at some high-profile targets,[2] but then he had a better idea: Instead of =
just using that SPAC to merge with one company, why not run it more like a =
fund? Use the SPAC to buy stock in some company, alongside other Pershing S=
quare funds, without spending the full $4 billion. Then use the money left =
over to hunt for=C2=A0<em>another=C2=A0</em>deal with=C2=A0<em>another=C2=
=A0</em>company; diversify your bets a bit.[3] Instead of one big deal, two=
 smaller ones.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then, best of all, Ackma=
n cooked up a way to tap the Pershing Square Tontine shareholders for=C2=A0=
<em>more=C2=A0</em>money for a=C2=A0<em>third=C2=A0</em>deal. He would issu=
e what he called SPARs (=E2=80=9Cspecial purpose acquisition rights=E2=80=
=9D) in a SPARC (=E2=80=9Cspecial purpose acquisition rights company=E2=80=
=9D) that could trade on the stock exchange and that entitled holders to in=
vest money in a=C2=A0<em>future=C2=A0</em>deal. Presumably when he did the =
third deal, he would tap the SPAR holders for cash and also give them=C2=A0=
<em>new=C2=A0</em>SPARs to invest in a fourth deal, etc. Pershing Square To=
ntine would transform from a one-shot blind pool to invest in a single gian=
t public company into a perpetual investment fund to invest in whatever Ack=
man thinks looks good.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was a good trad=
e, we talked about it a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc3BhY3M/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6466d52a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> couple</a> of times, and=C2=A0I quite liked it, but I=
 guess the Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMTkvcGVyc2hpbmctc3F1YXJlLWRlY2lkZXMtbm90LX=
RvLXByb2NlZWQtd2l0aC11bml2ZXJzYWwtbXVzaWMtZGVhbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
ad75e93" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =
did not</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bill Ackman will b=
uy a stake in Universal Music Group with his hedge fund rather than his bla=
nk-check company after opposition from investors and U.S. regulators.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ackman=E2=80=99s special purpose acquisition com=
pany will withdraw its offer for a 10% stake, he said in a letter on Monday=
. His hedge fund will assume the share purchase agreement, and buy 5% to 10=
% of the music label, UMG=E2=80=99s owner Vivendi SE said in a separate sta=
tement. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pershing Square Tontine said th=
at while it had multiple discussions with the U.S. Securities and Exchange =
Commission trying to address the regulator=E2=80=99s concerns, it =E2=80=9C=
did not believe PSTH would be able to consummate the transaction.=E2=80=9D =
The regulator was particularly worried that the deal structure wouldn=E2=80=
=99t qualify for New York Stock Exchange rules.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The SEC raised =E2=80=9Cdeal killer=E2=80=9D concerns last week and =
=E2=80=9Cstopped=E2=80=9D the deal, Ackman said in a CNBC interview. Ackman=
 said holders of the blank-check company who are upset should complain to t=
he SEC.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pershing Square Tontine will go and=
 do a =E2=80=9Cvery straightforward=E2=80=9D merger deal, Ackman told CNBC.=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh well! Here=E2=80=99s <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3N3aXJlLmNvbS9uZXdzL2hvbWUvMjAyMTA3MTgwMDUwMzMvZW4vUGVyc2=
hpbmctU3F1YXJlLVRvbnRpbmUtSG9sZGluZ3MtTHRkLi1SZWxlYXNlcy1MZXR0ZXItdG8tU2hhc=
mVob2xkZXJz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea337e72" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the letter</a>, which says: =E2=80=9CO=
ur decision to seek an alternative initial business combination (=E2=80=9CI=
BC=E2=80=9D) was driven by issues raised by the SEC with several elements o=
f the proposed transaction =E2=80=93 in particular, whether the structure o=
f our IBC qualified under the NYSE rules.=E2=80=9D I am not exactly sure wh=
at the problem is, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly9ueXNlLndvbHRlcnNrbHV3ZXIuY2xvdWQvbGlzdGVkLW=
NvbXBhbnktbWFudWFsL2RvY3VtZW50P3RyZWVOb2RlSWQ9Y3NoLWRhLWZpbHRlciFXS1VTLVRBT=
C1ET0NTLVBIQy0lN0IwNTg4QkY0QS1EM0I1LTRCOTEtOTRFQS1CRTlGMTcwNTdERjAlN0QtLVdL=
VVNfVEFMXzU2NjclMjN0ZWlkLTEw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB54d2e108" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Rule 102.06</a> of th=
e New York Stock Exchange=E2=80=99s Listed Company Manual says that a SPAC =
merger has to have =E2=80=9Ca fair market value equal to at least 80% of th=
e net assets held in trust,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and Pershing Square Tontine Holdi=
ngs was only planning to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc3BhY3MjZm9=
vdG5vdGUtMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d1e6fed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> spend about 74% of its money</a> on t=
he Universal Music shares, keeping the other 26% for its next deal.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a general matter, U.S. securities law is not pa=
rticularly fond of public companies that are set up as general-purpose inve=
stment funds. There are certain types of public investment funds that are a=
llowed =E2=80=94=C2=A0most notably, mutual funds, but also SPACs, business =
development companies, real estate investment trusts, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
nd they are all subject to pretty strict rules. Ackman=E2=80=99s public hed=
ge-fund-y fund, Pershing Square Holdings, is incorporated in Guernsey and t=
rades in Amsterdam and London; it=E2=80=99s not an idea that really works i=
n the U.S. Ackman=E2=80=99s proposed deal for Universal Music sort of looke=
d like it was transforming Pershing Square Tontine into a general-purpose i=
nvestment fund, and you can see why the SEC got nervous.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Still, I hope that whatever Pershing Square Tontine ends up d=
oing for its =E2=80=9Cvery straightforward=E2=80=9D (and large) merger, it =
finds a way to include some SPARs. Those were cool.</p><table class=3D"head=
er" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Google and accidents</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Imagine being omniscient. You know eve=
rything that is happening in the world, as it happens, and you can synthesi=
ze all that massive data in useful ways that allow you to understand it at =
a deep level. How would you use all that knowledge and understanding to=C2=
=A0<em>make money? </em>[4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a finan=
cial column, and I assume that the most obvious answer is that you=E2=80=99=
d use your omniscience to buy financial assets that are going to go up. Inv=
esting seems like=C2=A0the most straightforward and lowest-effort way to tr=
ansform information and understanding=C2=A0into money. Buy the stock of the=
 biotech company that has found a miracle cancer cure but not announced it =
yet, buy the cryptocurrency that=E2=80=99s about to take off, whatever.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But maybe that=E2=80=99s wrong. Knowing and un=
derstanding everything that is happening might not give you perfect foresig=
ht into the future, and some strands of the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL=
3dpa2kvRWZmaWNpZW50LW1hcmtldF9oeXBvdGhlc2lzI1dlYWssX3NlbWktc3Ryb25nLF9hbmRf=
c3Ryb25nLWZvcm1fdGVzdHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3646032c" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">efficient market hypothesi=
s</a> claim that you can=E2=80=99t beat the market even with good inside in=
formation. Maybe there are better ways to use your omniscience.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could have a very very very stylized model of Goog=
le that says that it is in the business of knowing and understanding everyt=
hing in the world =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9COur mission is to organize the wo=
rld=E2=80=99s information and make it universally accessible and useful,=E2=
=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.26=
0023/aHR0cHM6Ly9hYm91dC5nb29nbGUv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB588149cf" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">it says</a> =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and that it is about as good as anyone at that business. It is =
not omniscient, but it is a reasonable approximation of omniscience. It doe=
s not know my most private thoughts, for instance, but it does=C2=A0know wh=
at I write in emails, which is pretty close.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">I have always found it weird that the modern companies that approac=
h closest to omniscience seem to be mainly in the business of=C2=A0<em>ad s=
ales</em>? Like, it turns out that the most economically valuable human act=
ivity =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one that gives you the most leverage on omniscienc=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0is tailoring advertisements to internet users?=C2=A0Alphab=
et Inc., Google's parent company, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2h=
pdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTY1MjA0NC8wMDAxNjUyMDQ0MjEwMDAwMTAvZ29vZy0yMDIwMTIzMS=
5odG0jaWQ1NWJlNzk5MmIzNzRlMWE5YTJiYzQ4ODg3ZGRiYjNmXzQ2/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB57d09c40" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" title=3D"page=
 33" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">had $182.5 billion of revenue last year</a>, of whic=
h $146.9 billion came from Google advertising.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">I can sort of see it? The thesis is something like =E2=80=9Cwe know eve=
rything that happens and what everyone wants, so if you are selling somethi=
ng we can get it to the people who will buy it; we are in the business of o=
rganizing and intermediating <em>commerce</em>, and we take our commission =
in the form of ad revenue.=E2=80=9D Amazon.com Inc., another big omniscienc=
e company, is not really in the ad business, but is in this business of org=
anizing and channeling all of commerce. And =E2=80=9Call of commerce=E2=80=
=9D is a reasonable answer for =E2=80=9Cwhat is the most economically=C2=A0=
valuable place to apply omniscience?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Still. Ads. Weird.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Google i=
s now in the business of helping insurance companies sell insurance by <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cH=
