<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Texas two-step</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies are sort of arbitrary things=
. You can create a corporation by filling out a form and paying a small fee=
. You can create as many as you want. If you have three different businesse=
s, you can have three separate corporations, or you can do them all out of =
one big corporation, or you can do them out of three corporations all owned=
 by one big holding corporation, or you can put a few other corporations in=
 between, whatever. As many as you want.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On=
e important fact about corporations is that they have limited liability: If=
 a corporation owes more money to creditors than it has, it goes bankrupt a=
nd the creditors take whatever money it has left. The=C2=A0<em>shareholders=
=C2=A0</em>of the corporation don=E2=80=99t generally owe any extra money. =
Generally speaking, the value of a corporation's stock can=E2=80=99t be les=
s than $0: If you buy stock in a company, and it goes bust, your stock may =
turn out worthless, but you won=E2=80=99t owe anything else.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">These two facts =E2=80=94=C2=A0corporations have limited =
liability, and you can make as many as you want =E2=80=94 might give you id=
eas. Let=E2=80=99s say you run a big business in a corporation, Big Co. It =
has=C2=A0lots of assets and lots of liabilities. Let=E2=80=99s say it has $=
10 billion of assets and $4 billion of liabilities. Big Co. should be worth=
 $6 billion, its net worth, its assets minus its liabilities.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if you split it into=C2=A0<em>two=C2=A0</em>c=
orporations? Start one company called Asset Co. and put the $10 billion of =
assets into it, with no liabilities. Start another company called Liability=
 Co. and put the $4 billion of liabilities into it, with no assets. Asset C=
o. should be worth $10 billion. Liability Co. has a net worth of negative $=
4 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0lots of liabilities, no assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
a corporation can=E2=80=99t generally have negative value=C2=A0<em>to its o=
wners</em>; corporate stock can=E2=80=99t be worth less than zero. So let=
=E2=80=99s say Liability Co. is worth $0. Asset Co. plus Liability Co. are =
worth $10 billion, which is more than they were worth ($6 billion) as a com=
bined company. Good trade!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a thing =
that, mechanically, you could do. For instance:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-=
type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Big Co. creates a new subsidiary, Asset Co.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big Co. contributes all of its assets to Asset Co.=
 in exchange for stock in Asset Co.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">Big Co. spins off the stock of Asset Co. to its shareholders (as a divide=
nd payable in Asset Co. stock).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bi=
g Co. renames itself Liability Co.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No=
w the former shareholders of Big Co. (worth $6 billion) have become the sha=
reholders of Asset Co. (worth $10 billion) and Liability Co. (worth $0). Th=
ey are better off. Meanwhile the former creditors of Big Co. are much worse=
 off: When Big Co. owed them $4 billion, it had plenty of money to pay them=
; now that Liability Co. owes them $4 billion, it has no money, and they wo=
n=E2=80=99t get paid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What stops you from d=
oing this? Well, if your liabilities are bonds or bank loans, there will pr=
obably be=C2=A0provisions in the contract saying you can=E2=80=99t do this =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0Big Co. can=E2=80=99t transfer all or substantially all of i=
ts assets, etc. But some liabilities won=E2=80=99t have provisions like tha=
t. In particular,=C2=A0<em>contingent tort liabilities=C2=A0</em>won=E2=80=
=99t have any contracts at all.=C2=A0If Big Co. got all its money by crashi=
ng cars into people or manufacturing asbestos, those people will sue it for=
 money, and in an economic sense those lawsuits will all be liabilities. Bu=
t they won=E2=80=99t be contractual liabilities (at least until you settle)=
;=C2=A0you=E2=80=99ll have no agreement with the people suing you about wha=
t you're allowed to do with your corporate structure.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Instead, there is a general legal principle about =E2=80=9Cfraud=
ulent transfers.=E2=80=9D This is a term of art referring to, you know, thi=
s sort of trade: If you have a company, and it owes people money, and you m=
ove all the assets out of the company so that it can=E2=80=99t pay off its =
creditors, then that is a =E2=80=9Cfraudulent transfer=E2=80=9D and a court=
 will not allow it.=C2=A0This principle is found in, for instance, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzExLzU0OA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB510aa4ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">Section 548 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code</a>, as well as in many states=
=E2=80=99 laws in the form of the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudW5pZm9ybWxhd3Mub3JnL2NvbW1=
pdHRlZXMvY29tbXVuaXR5LWhvbWU_Q29tbXVuaXR5S2V5PTQyMjZhZTdjLTkxYzAtNGNlOS1iND=
g4LTg1MjBkYmMzOWVhMyM6fjp0ZXh0PVRoZSUyMFVuaWZvcm0lMjBGcmF1ZHVsZW50JTIwVHJhb=
nNmZXIlMjBBY3QsdGhlJTIwVW5pZm9ybSUyMFZvaWRhYmxlJTIwVHJhbnNhY3Rpb24lMjBBY3Qu=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB397d41a9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">Uniform Fraudulent Transfer Act</a>.[5] There are=
 specific details and borderline cases to consider, and the law here can be=
 complex, but the point is that the super-obvious trade I laid out above wo=
uld be a fraudulent transfer and a court would not allow it. The Liability =
Co. creditors would be able to go after Asset Co.=E2=80=99s assets to get t=
heir debts paid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, however, is another =
form of the trade:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: =
40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big Co. reincor=
porates in the state of Texas.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big=
 Co. does a=C2=A0<em>merger</em> into two companies, Asset Co. and Liabilit=
y Co. Usually a =E2=80=9Cmerger=E2=80=9D involves two companies becoming on=
e new company, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdGF0dXRlcy5jYXBpdG9sLnRleGFzLmdvdi9Eb2NzL0JPL2=
h0bS9CTy4xMC5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB129d4b7d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Texas law</a> allows a thing ca=
lled a =E2=80=9Cdivisive merger,=E2=80=9D in which one company =E2=80=9Cmer=
ges=E2=80=9D and becomes two new companies.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Asset Co. gets the assets, Liability Co. gets the liabilities, an=
d former Big Co. shareholders get shares of both.</li></ol><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">This sounds like the same thing as the spinoff version I laid =
out above. But it is different in one small weird way, which is that there =
is a sense among lawyers that a =E2=80=9Cmerger=E2=80=9D is not a =E2=80=9C=
transfer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0For instance, if Small Co. has a lease on some offi=
ce space, the lease might say "Small Co. may not transfer or assign this le=
ase,=E2=80=9D because the landlord wants to deal with Small Co. and not som=
e random other tenant. Small Co. can=E2=80=99t just sell the lease to some =
other company.=C2=A0But if Small Co. merges with Medium Co., that=E2=80=99s=
 different: Its corporate form has changed, but the-company-formerly-known-=
as-Small-Co. is still using the office space and paying the rent, so it wou=
ld be a little weird to say that it has violated the lease. And so often me=
rgers are not treated as transfers for various relevant legal purposes.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usually this is fine because a merger means co=
mbining two companies into one company, but in Texas a =E2=80=9Cmerger=E2=
=80=9D can mean splitting one company into two companies and things can get=
 weird. As <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2450391=
9.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY3JlZGl0c2xpcHMub3JnL2NyZWRpdHNsaXBzLzIwMjEvMDcvdG=
hlLXRleGFzLXR3by1zdGVwLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe759631e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Adam Levitin write=
s</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why would it matter that=
 a division is defined as a "merger" under Texas law? =C2=A0Because the Tex=
as Business Organizations Code provides that a merger operates "without ...=
 =C2=A0any transfer or assignment having occurred." =C2=A0The thinking is t=
hat if there's no transfer in a divisive merger, then there cannot be a fra=
udulent transfer.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is that righ=
t? Nobody knows! Levitin goes on:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Now, it is far from clear that Texas's fraudulent transfer law--or any o=
ther jurisdiction's--would defer to the Texas Business Organizations Code r=
egarding whether there is a transfer, but there's no law on that point (but=
 it has gotten some consideration in=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmF5bG9yLmVkdS9jb25=
0ZW50L3NlcnZpY2VzL2RvY3VtZW50LnBocC8xMTY4MTAucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
8e0de959" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;">this thoughtful law review comment</a>).</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I guess it=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24503919.260023/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vYnVzaW5lc3MvaGVhbHRoY2FyZS1waGFybWFjZXV0aWNhbHMvZXhjbHVz=
aXZlLWpqLWV4cGxvcmluZy1wdXR0aW5nLXRhbGMtbGlhYmlsaXRpZXMtaW50by1iYW5rcnVwdGN=
5LXNvdXJjZXMtMjAyMS0wNy0xOC8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6588d2f9" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">worth a shot</a>:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Johnson &amp; Johnson is exploring=
 a plan to offload liabilities from widespread Baby Powder litigation into =
a newly created business that would then seek bankruptcy protection, accord=
ing to seven people familiar with the matter.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">During settlement discussions, one of the healthcare conglomerate=E2=80=
=99s attorneys has told plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers that J&amp;J could purs=
ue the bankruptcy plan, which could result in lower payouts for cases that =
do not settle beforehand, some of the people said. Plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawy=
ers would initially be unable to stop J&amp;J from taking such a step, thou=
gh could pursue legal avenues to challenge it later. ...</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">J&amp;J faces legal actions from tens of thousands of plainti=
ffs alleging its Baby Powder and other talc products contained asbestos and=
 caused cancer. The plaintiffs include women suffering from ovarian cancer =
and others battling mesothelioma. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">J&amp=
;J is now considering using Texas's =E2=80=9Cdivisive merger=E2=80=9D law, =
which allows a company to split into at least two entities. For J&amp;J, th=
at could create a new entity housing talc liabilities that would then file =
for bankruptcy to halt litigation, some of the people said.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">The maneuver is known among legal experts as a Texas two-s=
tep bankruptcy, a strategy other companies facing asbestos litigation have =
used in recent years.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It does =
seem =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wrong? Like, obviously, if you run a big company that h=
as big liabilities, you=E2=80=99d like to be able to=C2=A0<em>just get rid =
of the liabilities</em>. And obviously companies have tried, and there are =
simple approaches (spin off the assets and leave the liabilities, etc.), an=
d those simple approaches=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t work=C2=A0</em>because gen=
erally it is=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>for a company to be able to just get ri=
d of its liabilities. It would be weird if there was a cheat where doing it=
 as a Texas two-step merger=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>work.</p><table class=3D=
"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
